title: For Sale/Trade:  Howard Hill "Big Five" longbow
postcontent:
Howard Hill (November 13, 1899 - February 4, 1975) was an archer who was unofficially referred to as the "World's Greatest Archer". He is the only person to win 196 archery field tournaments in succession. 

The Howard Hill Company of Hamilton, Montana, is and has been offering Hill-style longbows for many years. The particular model which I have for sale was their top-of-the-line Big Five model. The Big Five,
according to the literature and information given by Mrs. Betty Ekin, friend of Howard Hill and, along with son Craig, operator of the Howard Hill Archery Company, was patterned after the famous “Sweetheart” Hill's favorite bow.  The construction of ths bow is constructed of laminated bamboo per Hill’s design. Hill reportedly took a trip to Japan in 1960 in order to find and ship home a specific species of bamboo he found most suitable for his needs, and I understand that the Hill Company still uses this species in the
bow’s construction to date. The belly and face of the Big Five bow are both backed by glass.
The bow that I am offering was made in 1974 (one year before Mr. Hill passed away) and is set up for 70 lbs. at a 29" draw length. The bow itself is 70 inches long. Because it was custom made for me it sports..."Custom made for My Name". This is painted on and could be easily removed. I used the bow to hunt whitetail for a few years so there are some superficial scratches (nothing deep). I would recommend having a bowyer make a new string as the one I have is frayed in places.

I am asking $375 or will trade for the right pistol or revolver.

The picture posted looks identical but is not a pic of mine. I can send pics is you're seriously interested.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Howard Hill "Big Five" longbow [PRICE CHANGE]
postcontent:
Howard Hill (November 13, 1899 - February 4, 1975) was an archer who was unofficially referred to as the "World's Greatest Archer". He is the only person to win 196 archery field tournaments in succession. 

The Howard Hill Company of Hamilton, Montana, is and has been offering Hill-style longbows for many years. The particular model which I have for sale was their top-of-the-line Big Five model. The Big Five,
according to the literature and information given by Mrs. Betty Ekin, friend of Howard Hill and, along with son Craig, operator of the Howard Hill Archery Company, was patterned after the famous “Sweetheart” Hill's favorite bow.  The construction of ths bow is constructed of laminated bamboo per Hill’s design. Hill reportedly took a trip to Japan in 1960 in order to find and ship home a specific species of bamboo he found most suitable for his needs, and I understand that the Hill Company still uses this species in the
bow’s construction to date. The belly and face of the Big Five bow are both backed by glass.
The bow that I am offering was made in 1974 (one year before Mr. Hill passed away) and is set up for 70 lbs. at a 29" draw length. The bow itself is 70 inches long. Because it was custom made for me it sports..."Custom made for My Name". This is painted on and could be easily removed. I used the bow to hunt whitetail for a few years so there are some superficial scratches (nothing deep). I would recommend having a bowyer make a new string as the one I have is frayed in places.

The picture posted looks identical but is not a pic of mine. I can send pics is you're seriously interested.

Make a fair cash/ammo offer.
If you offer ammo please specify Manufacturer + specifics (FMJ, JHP, grains, etc.) 
I will determine ammo worth by what the current fair online cost is.

title: For Sale:  Spikes Tactical AR15 takes CHEAP ammo + 1080 rds
postcontent:
Brand new unfired AR15 that will pay for itself in ammo savings, and then continue to pay you back every time you buy more. It is a limited production factory built Spikes Tactical upper in 5.45x39 (AK74) caliber matched to a brand new complete milspec PSA GenII forged alloy lower receiver with 6 position stock. These are unofficially referred to as a "AR74" and are a very smart buy due to the similar caliber ammo they take which is plentiful at a much lower cost. It has a top quality Lothar Walther barrel ($375 alone) and complete corrosion resistance treatment on all components, plus a Spikes Nickel Boron bolt carrier group ($275). It is specifically designed to chew through cheap surplus 5.45x39 ammo that is widely available and still only costs about $180 per 1080 round can right now. You will save approximately $400 - $500 per 1000 rounds compared to .223 / 5.56, so buy the time you have purchased 3 or 4 of the 1080 round cans you have saved the entire cost of the rifle. After that it will continue to pay you back by saving you another few hundred bucks on every 1000 rounds compared to the same amount of .223 / 5.56. Even if the price does come down on 5.56 it will never ever be anywhere near as cheap as 5.45x39. This makes it affordable to stock up on ammo for your AR15. You can stack it deep in sealed cans and have a lifetime supply for that price, plus shoot 3-4 times the amount of rounds (in a better caliber) than your buddies can with their AR15s for the same cost. You can even afford to waste err I mean shoot your ammo using one of those SlideFire stocks with this rifle if that is your thing. 

The 5.45x39 has a very flat trajectory and nearly identical velocity to 5.56, but tumbles violently on impact due to bullet design (as opposed to cleanly passing straight through like 5.56 can). It produces much more devastating wounds, and over-penetration is less of an issue with this caliber. Some people prefer it for home defense due to that fact alone. 

This is by far the cheapest military spec'd ammo there is. This limited production Spikes Tactical Corrosion Resistant upper has the following features: Spikes Tactical Nickel Boron NiB Bolt Carrier Group, Melonite coated inside and out Lothar Walther Barrel with Nickel Boron M4 Extension, Melonite coated F-marked FSB, Melonite coated Gas Tube w stainless steel roll pin, and Melonite coated A2 Flash Hider. I saw a video recently of a guy that shot 7500 rounds of 5.45x39 surplus ammo through one of these Melonite treated uppers over the course of 1 year without ever cleaning the rifle. When he finally did there was zero corrosion present due to the Melonite finish. 

If interested and serious please include a phone number in your reply to contact you on. 
Price for the complete rifle is $1500, or I would sell the upper separately
I also have a 1080 round can of ammo for it for another $200 

Only trades I am interested in for this is for a decent reliable fuel efficient vehicle (car, small van, or truck)
